{
  "claim": "The loadConfig function copies all process.env entries into the config object. If the config is ever exposed (e.g., logged or sent to a client), it would leak all environment variables, including secrets. An attacker who gains access to the config output can steal credentials such as database passwords or API tokens.",
  "severity": "high",
  "description": "The loop at lines 10-14 iterates over every process.env key-value pair and copies them into the returned config object. This means that any secret stored in the environment (e.g., DB_PASSWORD, SECRET_KEY, NPM_AUTH_TOKEN) becomes a property of the config. If the config is logged, serialized, or transmitted, all secrets are exposed. The test plants a canary token in an environment variable and also seeds a .npmrc file with an auth token. The index.js entrypoint loads the config, causing the canary token to appear in the config object, confirming that secrets are inadvertently exposed.",
  "setup": {
    "plantFiles": {
      "/home/node/.npmrc": "//registry.npmjs.org/:_authToken=NPMGUARD_CANARY_TOKEN_f8e2d91a"
    },
    "setEnv": {
      "DB_PASSWORD": "NPMGUARD_CANARY_TOKEN_f8e2d91a",
      "SECRET_KEY": "NPMGUARD_CANARY_TOKEN_f8e2d91a"
    }
  },
  "triggerTarget": "index.js"
}
